  <section class="faq-section" aria-labelledby="faq-heading">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-eyebrow">Common Questions</div>
      <h2 id="faq-heading">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <div class="faq-list">
        <details class="faq-item" id="faq-1">
          <summary class="faq-question">
            How much PSU wattage do I need for my PC build?
            <svg class="faq-chevron" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" aria-hidden="true"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <p>The PSU wattage you need depends on your CPU and GPU power draw plus a safety buffer. A modern RTX&nbsp;5080 + Ryzen&nbsp;7&nbsp;9800X3D system needs at minimum 850W, accounting for the RTX&nbsp;5080's 540W transient peak plus CPU and other components. VoltForge calculates this precisely using published Cybenetics transient multipliers — not just a simple TDP sum.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="faq-item" id="faq-2">
          <summary class="faq-question">
            What PSU do I need for the RTX 4090?
            <svg class="faq-chevron" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" aria-hidden="true"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <p>The RTX 4090 has a 450W TBP but can spike to 707W (1.57× transient multiplier) in sub-millisecond bursts. Paired with a high-end CPU like the i9-14900K (253W sustained), your total transient peak can exceed 960W. NVIDIA officially recommends a minimum 850W PSU, but a 1000W ATX 3.1 PSU with a native 12V-2x6 connector provides the safest margin.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="faq-item" id="faq-3">
          <summary class="faq-question">
            What is ATX 3.1 and do I need it?
            <svg class="faq-chevron" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" aria-hidden="true"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <p>ATX 3.1 is the current power supply standard (2024 revision) designed to handle modern GPU transient power spikes of up to 200% of rated wattage for 100 microseconds. It introduces the 12V-2x6 connector (successor to 12VHPWR) with improved locking and fire-prevention features. For RTX&nbsp;5090, 5080, RTX&nbsp;4090, or any GPU above 300W TBP, an ATX&nbsp;3.1 PSU is strongly recommended.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="faq-item" id="faq-4">
          <summary class="faq-question">
            Is 650W enough for a gaming PC?
            <svg class="faq-chevron" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" aria-hidden="true"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <p>650W is enough for mid-range gaming builds using GPUs up to RTX&nbsp;4070 or RX&nbsp;7800&nbsp;XT paired with a 65W TDP CPU. However, it is <strong>not</strong> sufficient for RTX&nbsp;4080/4090/5080/5090 class GPUs — these cards have transient peaks of 480W–900W, which can exceed a 650W PSU's instantaneous delivery capacity even if the steady-state draw appears lower.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="faq-item" id="faq-5">
          <summary class="faq-question">
            What is the difference between 80 PLUS Gold, Platinum, and Titanium?
            <svg class="faq-chevron" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" aria-hidden="true"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <p>80 PLUS certifications measure PSU efficiency at 20%, 50%, and 100% load. Gold achieves ≥87–90% efficiency, Platinum achieves ≥89–92%, and Titanium achieves ≥92–96%. A Titanium PSU running 8 hours/day saves roughly $15–25/year in electricity compared to Bronze at US average electricity rates. Over 5 years, Titanium can pay for its price premium.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="faq-item" id="faq-6">
          <summary class="faq-question">
            Why does my GPU need more than its rated TDP from the PSU?
            <svg class="faq-chevron" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" aria-hidden="true"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <p>Modern GPUs draw significantly more power in microsecond transient spikes than their rated TBP (Total Board Power). The RTX&nbsp;5090, for example, is rated at 575W but can spike to 900W+ for sub-millisecond durations. A PSU that can only deliver 575W continuously may trip its over-current protection during these spikes, causing system crashes, shutdowns, or long-term PSU damage.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="faq-item" id="faq-7">
          <summary class="faq-question">
            How much does it cost to build a gaming PC in 2025?
            <svg class="faq-chevron" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" aria-hidden="true"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <p>A budget gaming PC in 2025 costs $500–$800 (Ryzen 5 / budget GPU). A mid-range build with RTX&nbsp;5060&nbsp;Ti or RX&nbsp;9070 costs $900–$1,400. A high-end gaming PC with RTX&nbsp;5080/5090 costs $2,000–$4,000+. These estimates include CPU, GPU, RAM, storage, motherboard, PSU, and case — but not monitor or peripherals.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="faq-item" id="faq-8">
          <summary class="faq-question">
            What PSU do I need for the RTX 5090?
            <svg class="faq-chevron" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" aria-hidden="true"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <p>The RTX 5090 requires a minimum 1000W PSU per NVIDIA. With its 575W TBP and a 1.57× transient multiplier, the card alone can spike above 900W. Combined with a high-end CPU, total transient peaks can exceed 1100W. A 1200W ATX&nbsp;3.1 PSU with a native 12V-2x6 port (not an adapter) is the safest recommended configuration.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="faq-item" id="faq-9">
          <summary class="faq-question">
            Should I use a 12VHPWR or 12V-2x6 connector?
            <svg class="faq-chevron" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" aria-hidden="true"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <p>If your PSU has both, always use the 12V-2x6 connector — it is the improved successor to 12VHPWR with a better locking mechanism and improved fire resistance. Never use an adapter cable to convert 8-pin PCIe connectors to 12VHPWR/12V-2x6 for GPUs above 350W, as adapters cannot safely handle the transient current demands.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="faq-item" id="faq-10">
          <summary class="faq-question">
            Is it worth getting a modular PSU?
            <svg class="faq-chevron" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" aria-hidden="true"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <p>Yes, a fully modular PSU is worth it for most builds. Modular PSUs let you connect only the cables you need, reducing cable clutter, improving airflow by 5–15%, making installation easier, and enabling custom cable sleeving. The price premium over non-modular units is typically $20–$50 and is well justified for any build above budget tier.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="faq-item" id="faq-11">
          <summary class="faq-question">
            How do I know if my PSU is failing?
            <svg class="faq-chevron" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" aria-hidden="true"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <p>Warning signs of a failing PSU include: random system shutdowns under load, PC refusing to power on, coil whine that worsens over time, visible burn marks or melted connectors, burning smell, BSOD errors correlated with GPU-intensive tasks, or voltage readings outside ±5% of rated values. PSUs typically last 5–10 years; replace any unit over 7 years old proactively.</p>
          </div>
        </details>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

